  "body": "**Is this a request for help?** (If yes, you should use our troubleshooting guide and community support channels, see http://kubernetes.io/docs/troubleshooting/.):\r\nNo\r\n\r\n**What keywords did you search in Kubernetes issues before filing this one?** (If you have found any duplicates, you should instead reply there.):\r\nHPA \r\nHPA limits \r\nscaling limits \r\nmax scale up\r\nmax scale down \r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n**Is this a BUG REPORT or FEATURE REQUEST?** (choose one):\r\nFeature Request\r\n\r\nHPA should have some specifications on limiting the number of pods that can be scaled up/down in a given scaling period. This is mainly useful for replica sets that receive bursts of traffic. Currently HPA will aggressively scale down based on CPU metrics which can be undesirable. At the moment this isn't a problem for scaling up because of a hard coded limit [here](https://github.com/kubernetes/kubernetes/blob/master/pkg/controller/podautoscaler/horizontal.go#L361-L365). Having a configurable specification can give cluster admins the ability to control this. If this is a desired feature I'd love to get my hands dirty and open a preliminary PR to get started. \r\n\r\n/cc @DirectXMan12 \r\n\r\n",
